<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Piano 100 | Study Guide - Doves Christian Academy</title>
    <style>
        * { margin: 0; padding: 0; box-sizing: border-box; }
        body { font-family: 'Segoe UI', Tahoma, Geneva, Verdana, sans-serif; background-color: #f5f5f0; padding: 20px; line-height: 1.6; transition: background-color 0.3s, color 0.3s; }
        body.dark-mode { background-color: #1a1a1a; color: #e0e0e0; }
        .guide-container { max-width: 900px; margin: 0 auto; background-color: white; border-radius: 12px; box-shadow: 0 4px 20px rgba(0,0,0,0.1); overflow: hidden; }
        .guide-header { background: linear-gradient(135deg, #2180B0 0%, #3E2723 100%); color: white; padding: 40px 30px; text-align: center; position: relative; }
        .section-title { color: #2180B0; font-size: 22px; font-weight: 600; margin-bottom: 15px; border-bottom: 3px solid #D4AF37; padding-bottom: 8px; margin-top: 25px; }
        .concept-card { background-color: #fafaf8; border: 1px solid #e0d5c5; border-radius: 6px; padding: 15px; margin-bottom: 15px; }
        body.dark-mode .concept-card { background-color: #2d2d2d; border-color: #444; }
        .study-tip { background-color: #d4edda; border-left: 4px solid #28a745; padding: 12px; margin: 15px 0; border-radius: 4px; color: #155724; }
        body.dark-mode .study-tip { background-color: #1a3a1a; color: #d4edda; }
        .dark-mode-toggle { position: absolute; top: 15px; right: 15px; background: rgba(255,255,255,0.2); border: none; color: white; padding: 8px 15px; border-radius: 20px; cursor: pointer; font-size: 12px; }
        table { width: 100%; border-collapse: collapse; margin-bottom: 20px; background: white; }
        body.dark-mode table { background: #2d2d2d; color: #e0e0e0; }
        th { background: #2180B0; color: white; padding: 12px; text-align: left; }
        td { border: 1px solid #e0d5c5; padding: 12px; }
    </style>
</head>
<body>

<div class="guide-container">
    <div class="guide-header">
        <button class="dark-mode-toggle" onclick="toggleDarkMode()">🌙 Dark Mode</button>
        <div style="font-size: 14px; letter-spacing: 2px; color: #F5E6D3; margin-bottom: 10px;">DCA | ACADEMIC PREPARATION</div>
        <h1>Piano 100 Study Guide</h1>
        <p>Advanced Theory, Harmonic Analysis & Technical Proficiency</p>
    </div>

    <div class="guide-body" style="padding: 30px;">
        <div class="intro-box" style="background: #FFF9F0; padding: 20px; border-left: 4px solid #D4AF37; margin-bottom: 30px; color: #3E2723;">
            <strong>🎹 Exam Strategy:</strong><br>
            This guide has been updated to reflect the <strong>New Assessment Topics</strong>. Focus heavily on Section 2 (Inversions) and Section 3 (Roman Numerals), as these carry the highest point value on the written exam.
        </div>

        <div class="section">
            <div class="section-title">1. Advanced Scale & Technical Mastery</div>
            <div class="concept-card">
                <strong>The Three Minor Forms:</strong>
                <ul>
                    <li><em>Natural:</em> Follows the key signature exactly.</li>
                    <li><em>Harmonic:</em> Raised 7th degree (ascending and descending).</li>
                    <li><em>Melodic:</em> Raised 6th and 7th ascending; lowered back to natural descending.</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
            <div class="concept-card">
                <strong>Fingering Standards:</strong> Remember that for B Major, the LH tonic (B) starts on <strong>Finger 4</strong> to accommodate the black-key clusters efficiently.
            </div>
            <div class="study-tip">
                <strong>Portfolio Update:</strong> Your scale submissions must now demonstrate <strong>4 full octaves</strong> with consistent tempo (parallel motion).
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="section">
            <div class="section-title">2. Interval Inversions & Theory</div>
            <table h>
                <tr>
                    <th>Original Interval</th>
                    <th>Perfect Inversion</th>
                    <th>Quality Change</th>
                </tr>
                <tr><td>Major 3rd</td><td>Minor 6th</td><td>Major becomes Minor</td></tr>
                <tr><td>Perfect 5th</td><td>Perfect 4th</td><td>Perfect stays Perfect</td></tr>
                <tr><td>Minor 2nd</td><td>Major 7th</td><td>Minor becomes Major</td></tr>
                <tr><td>Augmented 4th</td><td>Diminished 5th</td><td>Aug. becomes Dim.</td></tr>
            </table>
        </div>

        <div class="section">
            <div class="section-title">3. Roman Numeral Analysis</div>
            <div class="concept-card">
                <strong>Diatonic Chord Qualities (Major Keys):</strong>
                <p>I (Major), ii (minor), iii (minor), IV (Major), V (Major), vi (minor), vii° (diminished).</p>
            </div>
            <div class="concept-card">
                <strong>Secondary Leading Tones:</strong> Look for accidentals that temporarily resolve to a chord other than the tonic (e.g., V/V).
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="section">
            <div class="section-title">4. Piano Mechanics & Pedaling</div>
            <div class="concept-card">
                <strong>Una Corda (Soft Pedal):</strong> On a grand piano, this shifts the entire keyboard action to the right so hammers strike only one or two strings instead of three, altering the <em>timbre</em>, not just volume.
            </div>
            <div class="concept-card">
                <strong>Sostenuto (Middle Pedal):</strong> Sustains only the notes that were held down at the precise moment the pedal was depressed.
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="section">
            <div class="section-title">5. Final Performance Checklist</div>
            <div class="concept-card" style="border-left: 5px solid #2180B0;">
                <strong>Required Portfolio Elements:</strong><br>
                • 4-Octave Major & Harmonic Minor Scales (Hands Together).<br>
                • Major & Minor Arpeggios (4 Octaves).<br>
                • Technical Etude (e.g., Czerny or Hanon).<br>
                • Two contrasting repertoire pieces from different eras.
            </div>
            <div class="study-tip">
                <strong>Review Window:</strong> Use the 🚩 "Flag for Review" feature during the digital test to revisit complex harmonic analysis questions before your final submission.
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>

        <button class="accordion">🧠 Final Review Challenge</button>
        <div class="panel">
            <div style="padding: 15px; background-color: #fff3cd; border-left: 4px solid #ffc107; margin: 15px 0; color: #333;">
                <p><strong>Scenario A:</strong> You are playing a scale that raises the 6th and 7th degrees only when moving upward, but plays according to the key signature when moving downward. Which scale form is this?</p>
                <details style="cursor: pointer; margin-top: 10px;">
                    <summary>Show Answer</summary>
                    Melodic Minor scale.
                </details>
            </div>

            <div style="padding: 15px; background-color: #fff3cd; border-left: 4px solid #ffc107; margin: 15px 0; color: #333;">
                <p><strong>Scenario B:</strong> You identify a <strong>Major 6th</strong> interval in a score. If you were to invert this interval, what would the new interval and quality be?</p>
                <details style="cursor: pointer; margin-top: 10px;">
                    <summary>Show Answer</summary>
                    Minor 3rd (The number 9 rule: 9 - 6 = 3; Quality flips from Major to Minor).
                </details>
            </div>

            <div style="padding: 15px; background-color: #fff3cd; border-left: 4px solid #ffc107; margin: 15px 0; color: #333;">
                <p><strong>Scenario C:</strong> In a piece written in C Major, you encounter a <strong>D minor chord</strong>. How would you label this using Roman Numeral Analysis?</p>
                <details style="cursor: pointer; margin-top: 10px;">
                    <summary>Show Answer</summary>
                    <strong>ii</strong> (Lower case indicates a minor triad on the second scale degree).
                </details>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</div>

<script>
    function toggleDarkMode() {
        document.body.classList.toggle('dark-mode');
        const isDark = document.body.classList.contains('dark-mode');
        document.querySelector('.dark-mode-toggle').textContent = isDark ? '☀️ Light Mode' : '🌙 Dark Mode';
    }

    var acc = document.getElementsByClassName("accordion");
    for (var i = 0; i < acc.length; i++) {
        acc[i].addEventListener("click", function() {
            this.classList.toggle("active");
            var panel = this.nextElementSibling;
            if (panel.style.maxHeight) {
                panel.style.maxHeight = null;
            } else {
                panel.style.maxHeight = panel.scrollHeight + "px";
            } 
        });
    }
</script>
</body>
</html>
